flowRoot.flowPara: Electric generation from woody biomass
cannot be considered renewable if there is no requirement to reforest the land
Biomass is a carbon friendly, reliable, renewable energy source.
CO2 is released into the atmosphere when biomass is burned
to generate electricity
Biomass consumes CO2 during the plant's life cycle, in many
cases, making the resultant biomass near-carbon neutral.
Critics: bioelectric power deforestation and contributes to CO2
emissions
Y1: SFI + USDA partnership
Y2: Tax refunds based on % SFI certified biomass
Y3: USDA will award states, grants based on SFI certified electricity
Y4: Mid-plan review; evaluate + readjust
Y10: Up for renewal
Y0: Apply tax to land developers
Y9: States receive funds from USDA
Y6: States receive funds from USDA
Y6: Initiate 4% corporate tax on plants that do not source 80% SFI certified woody biomass
With some modifications to plant design, biomass can be used alongside natural gas and coal
Co-locate biomass with weather-dependent renewable energy sources to stabilize the grid.
Coal plants are being retired (66.8 GW since 2012) due to competition from natural gas
Need to replace this electric source with reliable energy to ensure US electric security
The emerging wood pellet industry can improve socio-economic status of coal-dependent &
impoverished communities in the Southeast, with the transition to the bioeconomy.
The pulp and paper industry in the U.S. values sustainability and has created certification standards to ensure best practice. Sustainable Forestry Initiative (SFI)
Wood pellet manufacturing facilities are an intermediary between
forests and bioelectric power plants
Wood pellet plants can implement SFI certified practices to ensure
carbon-friendly biomass
Incentivize wood pellet facilities to source woody biomass from sustainably certified forests
Wood pellet manufacturing plants receive tax incentives to
implement best-practice standards analogous to the "SFI Fiber Sourcing Standard" certification program.
States are encouraged to update their respective Renewable Energy Portfolios (REPs):
- bioelectric power plants are required to source sustainably certified biomass
The USDA will award state governments funding to promote the development of carbon-friendly bioelectric power
Forests benefit from increased land value (wood pellets source)
- US forests are protected from land development
Bioelectric power is realized in a responsible manner and the Southeast retain a vital economic partner (EU)
The European Union is transitioning coal plants to burn biomass to CO2
Failure to sustainably source wood pellets could result in the loss of a vital trade
partner to vulnerable rural communities in the Southeast US
The proposed Clean Power Plan (CPP) was halted by a Supreme Court decision
in 2017 amidst backlash from 29 states and industry groups.
Biomass was not recommended in the CPP due to the controversy
in calculating its net carbon emissions.
Biomass: plant materials; e.g. crop residues, switch grass, corn
Woody biomass: biomass sourced from trees and shrubs
Wood pellets: common form of biomass that is easy to
package/ transport increases the energy density of woody
residues, and can be made from any part of the tree
and wood waste
Bioelectric power: Electric generation fired from biomass
